Repot this Hairy Rock Fig Tree with me! 🪴

How cool is this Ficus glumosa from South Africa? It’s also known as the Hairy Rock Fig! The younger parts of the tree such as the branchlets, petioles and leaves are covered with soft, golden hairs called trichomes. Ficus species are quite adaptive being able to tolerate various ranges of light, moisture and soil conditions which makes them survival specialists! 🙌🏽🌳

Soil plays a big role in supporting plant growth and Ficus like a nutrient rich and well-draining potting mix. I’m using Espoma’s Organic Potting Soil Mix because it’s fortified with limestone to adjust PH which i love because ficus thrive in a more neutral soil! 😊

Dioscorea mexicana 🌿 

This plant is also known as “Turtle Plant” because the caudex has polygonal sections similar to a turtle shell. 🐢🌱 

A caudex is a modified stem that stores water and nutrients which helps the plant adapt to dry conditions. 

Fun fact: Dioscorea mexicana’s caudex is edible and apparently it tastes like sweet potatoes. 😃🍠😋

Another interesting fact is that these plants are dioecious, which means that every individual plant is either male or female.  The plants either have only male reproductive organs(stamens) or only female reproductive parts(pistils). 🪴💚

Water my epiphytic plants with me 💦🌿🪵 

Epiphytes are plants that grow on other plants for physical support. Epiphytes are not parasitic plants and they don’t negatively affect the host plant, which is typically a tree. Instead, they live in a harmonious way. 😌🍃

Without soil, epiphytic plants acquire water through rainfall and humidity and they get their nutrients from forest debris that accumulates around them. 

These mounted epiphytes need more moisture than plants in pots. So I water them two to four times a week, depending upon how hot or dry my conditions are.

Amethyst Aura 😍💜✨

Have you ever seen anything like it??? 

Amethyst is a lilac variety of quartz formed inside volcanic rocks referred to as basalts. “Aura” refers to the iridescent coatings composed of fine metals which have been vapor deposited on the stone. 

Some people believe crystals have healing or special powers to them. I absolutely do not believe this in the slightest 🤭 crystals are just beautiful minerals.

Hydrophobicity 🪷💦 

Lotus leaves are specially adapted with microscopic, waxy hairlike structures which minimizes water adhesion to the leaves. This means that the leaves are extremely difficult to wet. Water beads up on the leaf’s surface and picks up any dirt particles as it rolls off the leaf making this plant self-cleaning. 

Isn’t that so cool?! 🫨 There’s actually a term for this phenomenon, it’s called The Lotus Effect.

Dischidia imbricata 🌿

A shingling type Dischidia is native to Southeast Asia from Vietnam to Indonesia. 

“Shingling” is a climbing behavior exhibited in which the plants stems root onto the surface of a tree or wall and the leaves lie flat resembling roofing shingles. 

Similarly to Hoya imbricata, Dischidia imbricata is also a myrmecophile species, meaning that it lives in symbiosis with ants and other organisms. Other than protecting the roots, the undersides of the leaves offer shelter to colonies of ants who, in turn, provide nutrients to the plant and protect them from foliage eating insects. 

Hoya and Dischidia are both genera of plants in the family Apocynaceae. One of the the main distinctions between Hoya and Dischidia is: Hoya produce large clusters of flowers, whereas Dischidia flowers are much smaller in comparison.

THIS Begonia makes me happy 🪴🥰💚 Named after the Natuna island in Indonesia, Begonia natunaensis is a rhizomatous type begonia that has beautiful round leaves! The word rhizomatous just means that it has a prominent horizontal growth habit so the stems of the plant grow across the soil surface whereas other begonias grow more upright. These type of begonias tend to have more larger leaves and their modified stems also store water which makes these types much more forgiving to under-watering and easier to grow! I’ve been in love with this plant for a while and I recently got this one from my dear friend Jacob @plants.choto 🌿✨ (I’ll link some online sources in my stories if you’re wanting to add one to you collection too!)

This strange plant is known by several different names: Rattle Skulls, Banana Hoya, Ant plant or Dischidia major 

An interesting fact about Dischidia major is that it’s a myrmecophile species; meaning that it lives in symbiosis with ants or other organisms. The modified leaves are hollow and serve as nesting space to small colonies of ants which provide nutrients to the plant from their wastes and protect it from animals and foliage eating insects.

What do you give a gardener for Christmas? If you don’t know what to get them, let me help! Here’s 5 gift ideas of things that I love & found to be useful for me in my garden: 

1. Gardening Gloves - most gardeners I know don’t actually use gloves but they really should! Gifting them a pair would most likely encourage them to take the extra step in protecting their hands from nicks and cuts. 

2. Plant Labels - these help recall what was planted, especially when it comes to seedlings. 

3. Gardening Tools - let me tell you, we can never have enough tools for the garden! 

4. Hand Soap & Lotion - working in the garden can be quite harsh on the skin so a nice set of hand soap & lotion can soothe overworked and dry hands.

5. Native Seeds - give them the gift of something to look forward to! Native seeds attract pollinators & local wildlife  and help support the soil while providing beauty for years to come! 

These all make excellent gifts individually but they can also be gathered together to create a gift basket like what I’ve done here! Feeling inspired?
